WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.680
Preface and Introduction of Up From Slavery.

00:04.960 --> 00:06.600
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:06.780 --> 00:09.700
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:10.200 --> 00:15.520
For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:15.760 --> 00:17.620
Recording by Andy Yu.

00:18.220 --> 00:21.540
Up From Slavery by Booker T. Washington.

00:22.040 --> 00:23.860
Preface and Introduction.

00:24.360 --> 00:29.500
This volume is dedicated to my wife, Margaret James Washington,

00:29.780 --> 00:32.880
and to my brother, John H. Washington,

00:33.320 --> 00:36.540
whose patience, fidelity, and hard work

00:36.540 --> 00:41.360
have gone far to make the work at Tuskegee successful.

00:42.260 --> 00:42.740
Preface.

00:42.960 --> 00:46.120
This volume is the outgrowth of a series of articles

00:46.120 --> 00:49.400
dealing with incidents in my life which

00:49.400 --> 00:53.180
were published consecutively in the Outlook

00:53.780 --> 00:56.940
While they were appearing in that magazine,

00:57.240 --> 01:01.740
I was constantly surprised at the number of requests which

01:01.740 --> 01:04.780
came to me from all parts of the country,

01:04.880 --> 01:07.940
asking that the articles be permanently

01:07.940 --> 01:09.920
preserved in book form.

01:10.400 --> 01:14.000
I am most grateful to the Outlook for permission

01:14.000 --> 01:16.160
to gratify these requests.

01:16.640 --> 01:19.900
I have tried to tell a simple, straightforward story

01:19.900 --> 01:22.700
with no attempt at embellishment.

01:22.700 --> 01:26.360
My regret is that what I have attempted to do

01:26.360 --> 01:29.180
has been done so imperfectly.

01:29.320 --> 01:31.720
The greater part of my time and strength

01:31.720 --> 01:35.160
is required for the executive work connected

01:35.160 --> 01:39.380
with the Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute

01:39.380 --> 01:44.900
and in securing the money necessary for the support

01:44.900 --> 01:46.040
of the institution.

01:46.400 --> 01:50.700
Much of what I have said has been written on board trains

01:50.700 --> 01:54.040
or at hotels or railroad stations

01:54.040 --> 01:56.780
while I have been waiting for trains

01:56.780 --> 02:00.520
or during the moments that I could spare

02:00.520 --> 02:03.360
from my work while at Tuskegee.

02:03.500 --> 02:06.900
Without the painstaking and generous assistance

02:06.900 --> 02:09.480
of Mr. Max Bennett Thrasher,

02:09.860 --> 02:13.500
I could not have succeeded in any satisfactory degree.

02:14.080 --> 02:14.900
Introduction.

02:15.680 --> 02:18.600
The details of Mr. Washington's early life

02:18.600 --> 02:21.980
as Flankley sat down in Up From Slavery

02:21.980 --> 02:25.440
do not give quite a whole view of his education.

02:25.960 --> 02:29.620
He had the training that a colored youth received

02:29.620 --> 02:34.020
at Hampton, which indeed the autobiography does explain,

02:34.300 --> 02:38.300
but the reader does not get his intellectual pedigree

02:38.300 --> 02:40.820
for Mr. Washington himself, perhaps,

02:41.000 --> 02:44.720
does not as clearly understand it as another man might.

02:45.120 --> 02:47.120
The truth is he had the training

02:47.120 --> 02:50.920
during the most impressionable period of his life

02:50.920 --> 02:52.940
that was very extraordinary,

02:53.460 --> 02:57.200
such a training as few men of his generation have had.

02:57.560 --> 02:59.500
To see its full meaning,

02:59.640 --> 03:02.740
one must start in the Hawaiian Islands

03:02.740 --> 03:04.980
half a century or more ago.

03:05.740 --> 03:09.920
There, Samuel Armstrong, a youth of missionary parents,

03:10.320 --> 03:13.260
earned enough money to pay his expenses

03:13.260 --> 03:16.960
at an American college equipped with a small sum

03:16.960 --> 03:20.920
and the earnestness that the undertaking implied.

03:21.240 --> 03:23.140
He came to Williams College

03:23.140 --> 03:26.660
when Dr. Mark Hopkins was president.

03:27.300 --> 03:31.560
Williams College had many good things for youth in that day,

03:31.660 --> 03:33.240
as it has in this,

03:33.460 --> 03:36.700
but the greatest was the strong personality

03:36.700 --> 03:39.060
of its famous president.

03:39.820 --> 03:43.400
Every student does not profit by a great teacher,

03:43.400 --> 03:46.180
but perhaps no young man ever came

03:46.180 --> 03:48.480
under the influence of Dr. Hopkins,

03:48.840 --> 03:52.660
whose whole nature was so right for profit

03:52.660 --> 03:55.560
by such an experience as young Armstrong.

03:56.440 --> 03:59.400
He lived in the family of President Hopkins

03:59.400 --> 04:04.780
and thus had a training that was wholly out of the common,

04:05.360 --> 04:08.160
and this training had much to do

04:08.160 --> 04:11.680
with the development of his own strong character,

04:11.680 --> 04:14.360
whose originality and force

04:14.360 --> 04:16.840
we are only beginning to appreciate.

04:17.540 --> 04:21.200
For this interesting view of Mr. Washington's education,

04:21.600 --> 04:25.980
I am indebted to Robert C. Austin, Esquire,

04:26.140 --> 04:29.320
Chairman of the Board of Trustees of Hampton Institute

04:29.320 --> 04:32.660
and the intimate friend of General Armstrong

04:32.660 --> 04:36.000
during the whole period of his educational work.

04:36.540 --> 04:40.860
In turn, Samuel Armstrong, the founder of Hampton Institute

04:40.860 --> 04:43.540
took up his work as a trainer of youth.

04:43.720 --> 04:45.900
He had very raw material,

04:46.180 --> 04:48.320
and doubtless most of his pupils

04:48.320 --> 04:51.500
failed to get the greatest lessons from him.

04:51.600 --> 04:55.720
But as he had been a particularly receptive pupil

04:55.720 --> 04:56.900
of Dr. Hopkins,

04:57.440 --> 05:00.520
so Booker Washington became a peculiarly

05:00.520 --> 05:02.300
receptive pupil of his.

05:02.620 --> 05:05.520
To the formation of Mr. Washington's character,

05:05.860 --> 05:09.400
then went the missionary CEO of New England.

05:09.400 --> 05:13.260
Influenced by one of the strongest personalities

05:13.260 --> 05:15.200
in modern education,

05:15.920 --> 05:19.260
and the wide reaching moral earnestness

05:19.260 --> 05:21.420
of General Armstrong himself.

05:21.860 --> 05:24.240
These inferences are easily recognizable

05:24.240 --> 05:26.080
in Mr. Washington today

05:26.080 --> 05:29.440
by men who knew Dr. Hopkins and General Armstrong.

05:29.800 --> 05:32.900
I got the cue to Mr. Washington's character

05:32.900 --> 05:36.180
from a very simple incident many years ago.

05:36.180 --> 05:39.760
I had never seen him and knew little about him,

05:39.820 --> 05:42.620
except that he was the head of a school

05:42.620 --> 05:44.240
at Tuskegee, Alabama.

05:44.680 --> 05:46.940
I had occasion to write to him

05:46.940 --> 05:51.000
and I addressed him as the Reverend Booker T. Washington.

05:51.340 --> 05:53.820
In his reply, there was no mention

05:53.820 --> 05:56.900
of my addressing him as a clergyman.

05:56.940 --> 06:00.060
But when I had occasion to write to him again

06:00.060 --> 06:02.920
and persistent in making him a preacher,

06:03.140 --> 06:05.960
his second letter brought a postscript.

06:05.960 --> 06:08.260
I have no claim to Reverend.

06:08.560 --> 06:10.640
I knew most of the colored men

06:10.640 --> 06:13.100
who had at the time had become prominent

06:13.100 --> 06:14.880
as leaders of their race,

06:14.980 --> 06:16.920
but I had not then known one

06:16.920 --> 06:20.160
who was neither a politician nor a preacher.

06:20.280 --> 06:22.960
And I had not heard of the head

06:22.960 --> 06:25.400
of an important colored school

06:25.400 --> 06:27.140
who was not a preacher.

06:27.460 --> 06:31.660
A new kind of man surely if he looks upon his task

06:31.660 --> 06:35.420
as an economic one instead of a theoretical one.

06:35.420 --> 06:39.960
I wrote him an apology for mistaking him for a preacher.

06:40.440 --> 06:42.920
The first time that I went to Tuskegee,

06:43.120 --> 06:45.320
I was asked to make an address

06:45.320 --> 06:47.320
to the school on Sunday evening.

06:47.740 --> 06:51.140
I sat upon the platform of the large chapel

06:51.140 --> 06:54.080
and looked forth on a thousand colored faces.

06:54.240 --> 06:58.840
And the choir of a hundred or more behind me

06:58.840 --> 07:01.360
sang a familiar religious melody

07:01.360 --> 07:05.280
and the whole company joined in the chorus unction.

07:05.880 --> 07:08.120
I was the only white man under the roof

07:08.120 --> 07:12.220
and the scene and the songs made an impression on me

07:12.220 --> 07:14.020
that I shall never forget.

07:14.540 --> 07:19.360
Mr. Washington arose and asked them to sing one after another

07:19.360 --> 07:23.200
all the old melodies that I had heard all my life.

07:23.260 --> 07:28.140
But I had never before heard them sung by a thousand voices

07:28.140 --> 07:31.880
nor by the voices of educated Negroes.

07:31.920 --> 07:35.200
I had associated them with the Negro of the past,

07:35.400 --> 07:39.060
not with the Negro who was struggling upward.

07:39.360 --> 07:42.700
They brought to my mind the plantation, the cabin,

07:42.900 --> 07:46.100
the slave, not the freedom in quest of education.

07:46.320 --> 07:49.160
But on the plantation and in the cabin,

07:49.600 --> 07:51.500
they had never been sung

07:51.500 --> 07:54.460
as these thousand students sang them.

07:54.460 --> 07:59.100
I saw again all the old plantations that I had ever seen.

07:59.420 --> 08:02.600
The whole history of the Negro ran through my mind

08:02.600 --> 08:06.200
and the inexpressible pathos of his life

08:06.200 --> 08:08.920
found expression in these songs

08:08.920 --> 08:11.680
as I had never before felt it.

08:11.960 --> 08:15.760
And the future, these were the ambitious use of the race

08:15.760 --> 08:18.920
at work with an earnestness that put to shame

08:18.920 --> 08:20.660
the conventional student life

08:20.660 --> 08:23.160
of most educational institutions.

08:23.720 --> 08:26.700
Another song rolled up along the rafters

08:26.700 --> 08:28.460
and as soon as silence came,

08:28.660 --> 08:32.860
I found myself in front of this extraordinary mass of faces

08:32.860 --> 08:34.780
thinking not of them,

08:34.860 --> 08:37.960
but of that long and unhappy chapter

08:37.960 --> 08:39.640
in our country's history,

08:39.940 --> 08:43.400
which followed the one great structural mistake

08:43.400 --> 08:45.560
of the fathers of the republic.

08:45.920 --> 08:49.060
Thinking of the one continuous great problem

08:49.060 --> 08:52.580
that generations of statesmen had wrangled over

08:52.580 --> 08:55.220
and a million men fought about

08:55.220 --> 08:59.320
and that had so drafted the mass of angry men

08:59.320 --> 09:03.840
in the southern states as to hold them back a hundred years

09:03.840 --> 09:07.660
behind their fellows in every other part of the world,

09:07.780 --> 09:09.320
in England, in Australia,

09:09.520 --> 09:12.040
and in the northern and western states.

09:12.360 --> 09:14.940
I was thinking of this dark shadow

09:14.940 --> 09:19.020
that had oppressed every large-minded statesman

09:19.020 --> 09:20.640
from Jefferson to Lincoln.

09:20.640 --> 09:24.740
These thousands young men and women about me

09:24.740 --> 09:26.260
were victims of it.

09:26.560 --> 09:29.560
I too was an innocent victim of it.

09:29.760 --> 09:34.020
The whole republic was a victim of that fundamental era

09:34.020 --> 09:37.060
of importing Africa into America.

09:37.420 --> 09:41.240
I held firmly to the first article of my faith

09:41.240 --> 09:43.900
that the republic must stand fast

09:43.900 --> 09:46.700
by the principle of a fair ballot.

09:46.920 --> 09:49.740
But I recalled the wretched mass

09:49.740 --> 09:52.140
that Reconstruction had made of it.

09:52.580 --> 09:55.260
I recalled the low level of public life

09:55.260 --> 09:57.320
in all the black states.

09:57.680 --> 10:01.500
Every effort of philanthropy seemed to have miscarried.

10:02.020 --> 10:06.760
Every effort at connecting abuses seemed of doubtful value

10:06.760 --> 10:11.620
and the race friction seemed to become severer.

10:11.900 --> 10:14.780
Here was the century-old problem

10:14.780 --> 10:18.720
in all its pathos seated, singing before me.

10:18.720 --> 10:21.180
Who were the more to be pitied,

10:21.280 --> 10:24.480
these innocent victims of an ancient wrong

10:24.480 --> 10:29.140
or I and men like me who had inherited the problem?

10:29.480 --> 10:33.300
I long ago thrown aside illusions and theories

10:33.300 --> 10:37.540
and was willing to meet the faces face to face

10:37.540 --> 10:41.880
and to do whatever in God's name a man might do

10:41.880 --> 10:45.380
towards saving the next generation from such a burden.

10:45.380 --> 10:49.980
But I felt the weight of 20 well-nigh hopeless years

10:49.980 --> 10:53.180
of thought and reading and observation

10:53.180 --> 10:55.960
for the old difficulties remained

10:55.960 --> 10:58.040
and new ones had sprung up.

10:58.160 --> 11:02.520
Then I saw clearly that the way out of a century of bundles

11:02.520 --> 11:05.800
had been made by this man who stood beside me

11:05.800 --> 11:08.440
and was introducing me to his audience.

11:08.940 --> 11:12.000
Before me was the material he had used.

11:12.000 --> 11:15.380
All about me was the indisputable evidence

11:15.380 --> 11:19.080
that he had found the natural line of development.

11:19.460 --> 11:23.060
He had shown the way time and patience and encouragement

11:23.060 --> 11:25.160
and work would do the rest.

11:25.580 --> 11:28.280
It was then more clearly than ever before

11:28.280 --> 11:31.040
that I understood the patriotic significance

11:31.040 --> 11:32.640
of Mr. Washington's work.

11:32.840 --> 11:36.060
It is this conception and of him

11:36.060 --> 11:38.880
that I have ever since carried with me.

11:38.880 --> 11:43.400
It is on this that his claim to our gratitude rests.

11:43.960 --> 11:46.200
To teach the Negro to read,

11:46.380 --> 11:48.780
whether English or Greek or Hebrew,

11:49.140 --> 11:50.480
bitters no paslips.

11:50.800 --> 11:52.380
To make the Negro work,

11:52.520 --> 11:55.140
that is what his master did in one way

11:55.140 --> 11:56.900
and hunger has done in another.

11:57.240 --> 12:00.740
Yet both these left sultan life were defounded.

12:00.840 --> 12:04.020
But to teach the Negro to do skillful work

12:04.020 --> 12:07.520
as men of all the races that have risen have worked,

12:07.520 --> 12:11.600
responsible work, which is education and character.

12:11.960 --> 12:16.320
And most of all, when Negroes so teach Negroes to do this,

12:16.500 --> 12:20.140
that they will teach others with a missionary zeal

12:20.140 --> 12:24.020
that puts all ordinary philanthropic efforts to shame.

12:24.380 --> 12:28.460
This is to change the whole economic basis of life

12:28.460 --> 12:30.740
and the whole character of a people.

12:31.200 --> 12:33.260
The plan itself is not a new one.

12:33.280 --> 12:35.660
It was worked out at Hampton Institute,

12:35.660 --> 12:38.540
but it was done at Hampton by white men.

12:38.880 --> 12:43.960
The plan had in fact been many times theoretically laid down

12:43.960 --> 12:47.200
by thoughtful students of sultan life.

12:47.740 --> 12:50.740
Handicrafts were taught in the days of slavery

12:50.740 --> 12:53.900
on most well-managed plantations.

12:54.380 --> 12:58.360
But Tuskegee is, neptuness, a brand new chapter

12:58.360 --> 13:00.380
in the history of the Negro

13:00.380 --> 13:03.840
and in the history of the naughtiest problem

13:03.840 --> 13:05.240
we have ever faced.

13:05.680 --> 13:08.980
It not only makes a carpenter of a man,

13:09.240 --> 13:11.480
it makes a man of a carpenter.

13:11.880 --> 13:15.580
In one sense, therefore, it is of greater value

13:15.580 --> 13:20.060
than any other institution for the training of men and women

13:20.060 --> 13:23.340
that we have from Cambridge to Palo Alto.

13:23.740 --> 13:27.440
It is almost the only one of which it may be said

13:27.440 --> 13:30.360
that it points the way to a new epoch

13:30.360 --> 13:33.540
in a large area of our national life.

13:33.960 --> 13:37.840
To work out the plan on paper or at a distance,

13:37.900 --> 13:39.220
that is one thing.

13:39.540 --> 13:43.740
For a white man to work it out, that too is an easy thing.

13:43.900 --> 13:46.760
For a colored man to work it out in the South,

13:47.120 --> 13:49.060
where in its constructive period,

13:49.220 --> 13:53.180
he was necessarily misunderstood by his own people

13:53.180 --> 13:54.920
as well as by the whites,

13:55.280 --> 13:58.980
and where he had to adjust it at every step

13:58.980 --> 14:01.120
to the strained race relations,

14:01.500 --> 14:05.420
that is so very difficult and more difficult a thing

14:05.420 --> 14:08.380
that the man who did it put the country

14:08.380 --> 14:10.940
under lasting obligations to him.

14:11.260 --> 14:15.060
It was not and is not a mere educational task.

14:15.620 --> 14:18.200
Anybody could teach boys trades

14:18.200 --> 14:20.780
and give them an elementary education.

14:21.180 --> 14:23.060
Such tasks have been done

14:23.060 --> 14:25.100
since the beginning of civilization,

14:25.100 --> 14:27.660
but this task had to be done

14:27.660 --> 14:30.400
with the rawest of raw material,

14:30.560 --> 14:34.580
done with the civilization of the dominant race,

14:34.940 --> 14:40.040
and so as not to run across race lines and social lines

14:40.040 --> 14:42.820
that are the strongest forces in the community.

14:43.100 --> 14:46.460
It had to be done for the benefit of the whole community.

14:46.680 --> 14:49.820
It had to be done, however, without local help

14:49.820 --> 14:52.700
in the face of direct poverty done by begging

14:52.700 --> 14:56.820
and done in spite of the ignorance of one race

14:56.820 --> 14:59.100
and the prejudice of the other.

14:59.380 --> 15:01.980
No man living had a harder task

15:01.980 --> 15:06.200
and a task that called for more wisdom to do it right.

15:06.620 --> 15:09.820
The true measure of Mr. Washington's success

15:09.820 --> 15:14.420
is then not his teaching the pupils of Tuskegee,

15:14.620 --> 15:17.100
nor even gaining the support

15:17.100 --> 15:20.200
of philanthropic persons at a distance,

15:20.200 --> 15:24.480
but this, that every Southern white man of character

15:24.480 --> 15:29.300
and of wisdom has been one to cordial recognition

15:29.300 --> 15:31.220
of the value of the work.

15:31.940 --> 15:36.660
Even men who held and still hold to the conviction

15:36.660 --> 15:41.380
that a mere book education for the Southern blacks

15:41.380 --> 15:45.180
under present conditions is a positive evil.

15:45.880 --> 15:49.140
This is a demonstration of the efficiency

15:49.140 --> 15:52.620
of the Hampton Tuskegee idea that stands

15:52.620 --> 15:55.440
like the demonstration of the value

15:55.440 --> 15:57.920
of democratic institutions themselves.

15:58.520 --> 16:00.620
A demonstration made so clear

16:00.620 --> 16:02.820
in spite of the greatest odds

16:02.820 --> 16:05.820
that it is no longer open to argument.

16:06.560 --> 16:10.620
Consider the change that has come in 20 years

16:10.620 --> 16:13.400
in the discussion of the Negro problem.

16:13.560 --> 16:15.500
Two of three decades ago,

16:15.500 --> 16:18.320
social philosophers, statisticians,

16:18.640 --> 16:22.520
and well-meaning philanthropists were still talking

16:22.520 --> 16:27.020
and writing about the deportations of the Negroes

16:27.020 --> 16:31.080
or about their settlement within some restricted area

16:31.080 --> 16:34.760
or about their settling in all parts of the union

16:34.760 --> 16:39.860
or about their decline through the neglect of their children

16:39.860 --> 16:42.680
or about the rapid multiplication

16:42.680 --> 16:46.640
until they should expel the whites from the South

16:46.640 --> 16:50.900
of every sort of nonsense under heaven.

16:51.680 --> 16:54.440
All this has given place to the simple plan

16:54.440 --> 16:59.320
of an indefinite extension among the neglected classes

16:59.320 --> 17:04.220
of both races on the Hampton Tuskegee system of training.

17:04.960 --> 17:08.180
The problem in one sense has disappeared.

17:08.180 --> 17:11.220
The future will have for the South

17:11.220 --> 17:14.880
swift of snow development of its masses

17:14.880 --> 17:17.420
and of its soil in population

17:17.420 --> 17:22.600
to the swift of slow developments of this kind of training.

17:23.280 --> 17:26.940
This change of view is a true measure

17:26.940 --> 17:28.740
of Mr. Washington's work.

17:29.260 --> 17:33.500
The literature of the Negro in America is colossal

17:33.500 --> 17:37.480
from political oratory through abolitionism

17:37.480 --> 17:40.940
to Uncle Tom's Cabin and Cotton is King,

17:41.240 --> 17:45.200
a vast mass of books which many men have read

17:45.200 --> 17:49.180
to the waste of good years and I among them.

17:49.740 --> 17:53.480
But the only books that I have read a second time

17:53.480 --> 17:57.440
or ever care gain to read in the whole list,

17:57.820 --> 18:02.460
most of them by tiresome and unbalanced reformers,

18:02.860 --> 18:05.640
are Uncle Remus and Up from Slavery.

18:05.640 --> 18:10.440
For these are the great literature of the subject.

18:10.880 --> 18:13.100
One has all the best of the past,

18:13.260 --> 18:16.440
the other foreshadows a better future

18:16.440 --> 18:19.840
and the men who wrote them are the only men

18:19.840 --> 18:23.820
who have written of the subject with that perfect frankness

18:23.820 --> 18:26.820
and perfect knowledge and perfect pose

18:26.820 --> 18:29.200
whose other name is genius.

18:30.120 --> 18:34.560
Mr. Washington has won a worldwide fame at an early age.

18:34.980 --> 18:39.380
His story of his own life already has the distinction

18:39.380 --> 18:42.760
of translation into more languages,

18:42.760 --> 18:46.040
I think than any other American book

18:46.040 --> 18:51.480
and I suppose that he has as large a personal acquaintance

18:52.160 --> 18:56.900
among men of influence as any private citizen now living.

18:58.180 --> 19:01.860
His only teaching at Tuskegee is unique.

19:02.370 --> 19:06.280
He lectures to his advanced students

19:06.280 --> 19:09.160
on the art of right living,

19:09.880 --> 19:13.620
not out of textbooks but straight out of life.

19:13.860 --> 19:16.920
Then he sends them into the country

19:16.920 --> 19:18.560
to visit Negro families.

19:19.340 --> 19:22.840
Such a student will come back with a minute report

19:22.840 --> 19:28.340
of the way in which the family that he has seen lives,

19:28.340 --> 19:30.820
what their earnings are,

19:31.240 --> 19:34.520
what they do well and what they do ill

19:34.520 --> 19:39.360
and he will explain how they might live better.

19:40.800 --> 19:44.360
He constructs a definite plan for the betterment

19:44.360 --> 19:46.400
of that particular family

19:46.400 --> 19:49.820
out of the resources that they have.

19:50.740 --> 19:53.140
Such a student, if he be bright,

19:53.460 --> 19:57.220
will profit more by an experience like this

19:57.220 --> 20:00.080
than he could profit by all the books

20:00.080 --> 20:05.780
on sociology and economics that ever were written.

20:06.620 --> 20:09.600
I talked with a boy at Tuskegee

20:09.600 --> 20:12.980
who had made such a study as this

20:12.980 --> 20:16.980
and I could not keep from contrasting his knowledge

20:16.980 --> 20:21.000
and enthusiasm with what I heard in a classroom

20:21.000 --> 20:25.340
at a Negro university in one of the southern states,

20:25.340 --> 20:28.000
which is conducted on the idea

20:28.000 --> 20:31.660
that a college course will save the soul.

20:32.680 --> 20:35.740
Here, the class was reciting a lesson

20:35.740 --> 20:39.660
from an abstruse textbook of economics,

20:41.120 --> 20:44.760
reciting it by rote with so obvious failure

20:44.760 --> 20:49.640
to assimilate it that the ways of labor was pitiful.

20:50.720 --> 20:53.300
I asked Mr. Washington years ago

20:53.300 --> 20:57.400
what he regarded as the most important result of his work

20:57.400 --> 21:00.980
and he replied, I do not know which to put first,

21:01.260 --> 21:03.940
the effect of Tuskegee's work on the Negro

21:03.940 --> 21:08.620
or the effect of the attitude of the white man to the Negro.

21:09.400 --> 21:13.780
The race divergence under the systems of miseducation

21:13.780 --> 21:16.040
was fast getting wider.

21:16.320 --> 21:20.600
Under the influence of the Hampton Tuskegee idea,

21:21.140 --> 21:25.480
the races are coming into a closer sympathy

21:25.480 --> 21:29.420
and into an honorable and helpful relation.

21:30.500 --> 21:33.860
As the Negro becomes economically independent,

21:34.400 --> 21:37.760
he becomes a responsible part of the southern life

21:37.760 --> 21:40.820
and the whites so recognize him

21:40.820 --> 21:44.100
and this must be from the nature of things.

21:45.240 --> 21:48.140
There is nothing artificial about it.

21:48.560 --> 21:52.720
It is development in a perfectly natural way

21:52.720 --> 21:57.020
and the southern whites not only so recognize it

21:57.020 --> 22:01.240
but they are imitating it in the teaching

22:01.240 --> 22:04.700
of the neglected masses of their own race.

22:05.800 --> 22:08.940
It has thus come about that the school

22:08.940 --> 22:14.100
was taking a more direct and helpful hold on life

22:14.100 --> 22:17.920
in the south than anywhere else in the country.

22:18.800 --> 22:22.240
Education is not a thing apart from life,

22:22.740 --> 22:25.360
not a system, nor a philosophy.

22:25.700 --> 22:29.500
It is a direct teaching how to live and how to work.

22:30.520 --> 22:34.560
To say that Mr. Washington has won the gratitude

22:34.560 --> 22:37.560
of all throughout southern white men

22:37.560 --> 22:40.180
is to say that he has worked

22:40.180 --> 22:43.200
with the highest practical wisdom

22:43.200 --> 22:45.680
at a large constructive task

22:45.680 --> 22:50.140
for no plan for the upbuilding of the freedom

22:50.140 --> 22:54.500
could succeed that ran counter to southern opinion.

22:55.300 --> 22:58.240
To win the support of southern opinion

22:58.240 --> 23:02.040
and to shape it was a necessary part of the task

23:02.040 --> 23:04.660
and this he has so well succeeded

23:04.660 --> 23:09.020
that the south has a sincere and high regard for him.

23:10.100 --> 23:13.520
He once said to me that he recalled the day

23:13.520 --> 23:17.700
and remembered it thankfully when he grew large enough

23:17.700 --> 23:23.100
to regard a southern white man as he regard a northern one.

23:24.040 --> 23:28.380
It is well for our common country that the day is come

23:28.380 --> 23:33.120
when he and his work are regarded as highly in the south

23:33.120 --> 23:35.820
as in the other part of the union.

23:36.460 --> 23:39.640
I think that no man of our generation

23:39.640 --> 23:44.940
has a more noteworthy achievement to his credit than this

23:44.940 --> 23:49.620
and it is an achievement of moral earnestness

23:49.620 --> 23:51.960
of the strong character of a man

23:51.960 --> 23:55.620
who has done a great rational service.

23:58.080 --> 24:01.480
Introduction by Walter H. Page.

24:02.320 --> 24:04.880
End of Preface and Introduction.

24:05.780 --> 24:08.740
Recording by Andy Yu, Mississauga, Canada.

24:12.760 --> 24:14.160
Thank you.

